Zacznijmy od struktury modeli mieszanych (z efektami staymi i losowymi).

Czym rni si efekty stae od losowych

Jedna skadowa

Rozgrzewska: zbir danych milk.

Dziesi krw, po cztery pomiary dla kadej. Pytanie: jaka jest rednia produkcja mleka na krow.

library(PBImisc)
head(milk)
##     cow milk.amount
## 1 cow A        21.4
## 2 cow A        27.2
## 3 cow A        25.1
## 4 cow A        24.5
## 5 cow B        26.8
## 6 cow B        22.2
library(lattice)
dotplot(cow~milk.amount, data=milk, xlab="milk production [kg/day]")

Czy atwo to policzy?

(srednie = with(milk, tapply(milk.amount, cow, mean)))

Sprbujmy bardziej zoonego modelu.

library(lme4)
(model1 <- lmer(milk.amount~(1|cow), data=milk))
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
## Formula: milk.amount ~ (1 | cow)
##    Data: milk
## REML criterion at convergence: 178.8841
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Std.Dev.
##  cow      (Intercept) 2.755   
##  Residual             1.732   
## Number of obs: 40, groups:  cow, 10
## Fixed Effects:
## (Intercept)  
##       27.01
(model3 <- lmer(milk.amount~(1|cow), data=milk, REML=FALSE))
## Linear mixed model fit by maximum likelihood  ['lmerMod']
## Formula: milk.amount ~ (1 | cow)
##    Data: milk
##      AIC      BIC   logLik deviance df.resid 
## 186.4866 191.5533 -90.2433 180.4866       37 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Std.Dev.
##  cow      (Intercept) 2.599   
##  Residual             1.732   
## Number of obs: 40, groups:  cow, 10
## Fixed Effects:
## (Intercept)  
##       27.02

Lets compare predicted average milk production per cow.

ocenaMR = unlist(ranef(model1)) + fixef(model1)
ocenaMM = unlist(ranef(model3)) + fixef(model3)
ocenaLM = c(0,model2$coef[-1]) + model2$coef[1]
cbind(srednie, ocenaLM, ocenaMR, ocenaMM)

Dwie zmienne jakociowe

Tym razem prawdziwy zbir danych

Mamy 1000 pomiarw dla 465 krw. Krowy rni si genotyem genu btn3a1. Chcemy sprawdzi czy jest zwizek genotypu a mlecznoci.

summary(milkgene)
##      cow.id      btn3a1  lactation      milk            fat       
##  Min.   :  1.0   1:915   1:409     Min.   : 1708   Min.   : 85.0  
##  1st Qu.: 83.0   2: 85   2:334     1st Qu.: 6320   1st Qu.:262.0  
##  Median :206.5           3:202     Median : 7379   Median :298.5

##  3rd Qu.:341.2                     3rd Qu.: 8653   3rd Qu.:338.0  
##  Max.   :465.0                     Max.   :13442   Max.   :713.0
bwplot(milk~lactation, data=milkgene, ylab="milk production [kg/day]")

Zbudujmy model z trzema efektami.

(model1 <- lmer(milk~btn3a1+lactation+(1|cow.id), data=milkgene))
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
## Formula: milk ~ btn3a1 + lactation + (1 | cow.id)
##    Data: milkgene
## REML criterion at convergence: 17303.63
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Std.Dev.

## Fixed Effects:
## (Intercept)      btn3a12   lactation2   lactation3   lactation4  
##      6699.4       -244.1       1307.0       1800.5       1669.3

Wycigamy predyktory dla efektw losowych.

u = ranef(model1, condVar =TRUE)
dotplot(u)
## $cow.id

Testy dla wspczynnikw

Test Walda

summary(model1)$coef
##              Estimate Std. Error   t value
## (Intercept) 6699.4479   81.07595 82.631752
## btn3a12     -244.0844  235.11697 -1.038140
## lactation2  1307.0367   84.63442 15.443323
## lactation3  1800.5379  102.10172 17.634747
## lactation4  1669.2723  176.44866  9.460385
tse = summary(model1)$coef[2,3]
2*pnorm(tse, lower.tail=T)
## [1] 0.2992048

Test ilorazu wiarogodnoci

modelWithBTN1 = lmer(milk~btn3a1+lactation+(1|cow.id), data=milkgene, REML=F)
modelWithoutBTN1 = update(modelWithBTN1, . ~ . -btn3a1)

logLik(modelWithBTN1)
## 'log Lik.' -8680.175 (df=7)
logLik(modelWithoutBTN1)
## 'log Lik.' -8680.716 (df=6)
anova(modelWithBTN1, modelWithoutBTN1)
## Data: milkgene
## Models:
## modelWithoutBTN1: milk ~ lactation + (1 | cow.id)
## modelWithBTN1: milk ~ btn3a1 + lactation + (1 | cow.id)
##                  Df   AIC   BIC  logLik deviance  Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)
## modelWithoutBTN1  6 17373 17403 -8680.7    17361                         
## modelWithBTN1     7 17374 17409 -8680.2    17360 1.0826      1     0.2981

Test permutacyjny (co nowego)

N = 1000
logs = replicate(N, logLik(lmer(milk~sample(btn3a1)+lactation+(1|cow.id), data=milkgene, REML=FALSE)))
mean(logs > logLik(modelWithBTN1))
## [1] 0.311

Test ilorazu wiarogodnoci dla efektw losowych

(fullModel <- logLik(model1<-lmer(milk~btn3a1+lactation+(1|cow.id), data=milkgene)))
## 'log Lik.' -8651.814 (df=7)
(modelWithoutCow <- logLik(model2<-lm(milk~btn3a1+lactation, data=milkgene)))
## 'log Lik.' -8773.775 (df=6)
(lDelta = as.numeric(modelWithoutCow - fullModel))
## [1] -121.9614
pchisq(- 2 * lDelta, 1, lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 5.487788e-55
pchisq(- 2 * lDelta, 409, lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 1

Test permutacyjny dla efektw losowych

milkgene2 = milkgene
N = 1000
logs = replicate(N, {
 milkgene2$cow.id = sample(milkgene2$cow.id);
 logLik(lmer(milk~btn3a1+lactation+(1|cow.id), data=milkgene2))})
mean(logs > logLik(model1))
## [1] 0
